<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRITNY FOX: A HIGH-VOLTAGE ROCK GROUP WITH A KISS OF METAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF ZEIGLER, The Allentown (Pa.) Morning Call 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Philadelphia's Britny Fox may look like your average heavy metal band, but the 
quartet has more on its mind than the usual heavy metal themes. 
</P>
<P>
"We are more hard rock than heavy metal," lead guitarist Michael Kelly Smith 
said during a recent telephone interview. "You can hear a lot of influences 
from AC-DC and Kiss, but we have developed our own style." 
</P>
<P>
The group's self-titled first release contains messages about helping out your 
fellow man -- unusual for hard rock -- but Smith is quick to point out that the 
band is not ready for the pulpit. 
</P>
<P>
"We're not trying to preach anything. If you read the lyrics, we have a 
message," Smith said, "but we don't base ourselves on that type of thing. We 
aren't trying to tell you what to do or what not to do. 
</P>
<P>
"The song 'Save the Weak' is saying to take a look around you and realize how 
good you might have it because a lot of people are less fortunate than us. 
Appreciate what you have," he explained. 
</P>
<P>
Another song, "Rock Revolution," deals with censorship in rock and pop music, a 
subject that Smith holds a hard line against. "That ("Rock Revolution") is 
about the PMRC (Parents Music Resource Center) and how stupid it is," Smith 
said. "Hard-rock bands always get the bad rap. They (the PMRC) act as though 
that is the worst thing going on in the world. It's OK to put violence on TV, 
but you can't have explicit lyrics. . . . " 
</P>
<P>
Despite its recent success, Britny Fox has also had its share of tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
When the band first formed, its members figured its lineup was set with Dean 
Davidson on vocals and rhythm guitar, Billy Childs on bass and former 
Cinderella members Smith on lead guitar and Tony Destra on the drums. But 
Destra was killed in an automobile accident. 
</P>
<P>
"It was a big blow and a real setback, but we wanted to carry on for his sake," 
Smith said. "He wouldn't have wanted us to quit. Things were going good, we had 
record company interests. We went too far to quit." The band pressed on and 
replaced Destra with Johnny Dee. 
</P>
<P>
Smith said that Britny Fox, which derives its name from Davidson's 18th-Century 
ancestry, has plans for a new album: "We plan on going into the studio this 
summer. The record should be out by the fall or the end of the year. We have 
songs left over from the last album's sessions, plus we've been working on 
material since then." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Profile 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
ROCK MUSIC; BRITNY FOX (MUSIC GROUP) 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
